Light Installation Code

Against the backdrop of the terrible events that are happening now in Ukraine, I wanted to tell you that the history of my personal fight for Ukraine is several decades long, moreover, my paternal family were victims of Stalin's brutal regime, which killed more than 10 million Ukrainians.

Therefore, behind my collections Code Ukraine, Light Installations Code, is my personal message and mission to show the world through art the antiquity and depth of Ukrainian history and culture, the uniqueness of Ukrainian traditions. The mission to show the world that Ukraine is and will be, and no evil will destroy the Ukrainian nation. 

Some articles emphasize this, for which I am grateful to the journalists. Read on Ukrainian or translate: https://zakordon.24tv.ua/istoriya-ukrayinka-yaka-stala-vidomoyu-novini-ukrayini-i-svitu_n1588365?fbclid=IwAR1GPqVHisLH9F7L71ZuJejC6DtDnTs7x99dZ3_5DU3p3BOFy8TfnqXkCq0&mibextid=Zxz2cZ

The beauty of Light Installation Art is the gold/mirror finishing on their sides… #perfection #uniquness #elegance in #art #fineart is the key to success.

Art as a Way of Anticipating War in the Works of the American-Ukrainian Artist Oksana Tanasiv

February 8, 2023, 6-9pm. Chilton & Chadwick, 279 Sound Beach, Old Greenwich, CT. Solo-art exhibition and presentation of Dollar Art series by Oksana Tanasiv. 

"My brushes are my weapon, and my paintings are my personal way of fighting against war, corruption and injustice," says Ukrainian-born Connecticut artist Oksana Tanasiv.
Back in 2011, Oksana started working on the Dollar Art collection, in which she used dollar bills as the main element to show her position against corruption, financial and political manipulation, and in one of her paintings she depicted Putin's henchman, then Ukrainian President Yanukovych, and predicted war.

The world, which in recent years has witnessed military conflicts initiated by Russia in the struggle for financial control, a gas war against Europe, and large-scale corruption schemes of Russian oligarchs, has faced economic aggression on a century-long scale. This is what prompted the artist to create her compositions.

Since then, several series have been created on this topic, and only today, with the full-scale war in Ukraine, these paintings are gaining a prophetic message. 

As the art historian and critic Katarina Zavodszka puts it in her article ‘The Iconography of vanitas and the Labor of Love – the Work of Oksana Tanasiv’: “The art as social commentary has been here – powerful, persuasive, and challenging our understanding of the world, but driven by personal convictions, Tanasiv perpetuates the subject matter. The matter has slid into perversion.” (Artem Atrium. June 2021.)

Taras Shevchenko is a special figure not only in the history of Ukrainian and world literature, but also in my personal life, whose work had a huge impact on my consciousness back in school when I studied his poetry. The material I received in the school curriculum was not enough for me, so I read other resources that were available at the time. One of the books that opened up the life of the genius to me in greater detail was Dmytro Krasytsky's book “Taras's Dawns”

It's hard to track the extent of the impact this book had on my childhood consciousness, but today I can say with certainty that both the book and Shevchenko's life had a fateful and profound impact on my entire life.

And today, when my paintings were acquired by the Shevchenko Museum in Toronto (2022), I can consider this fact with special trepidation as a special "touch" to the timeless name of a world genius. 

But my biggest dream is still to visit the historical landmark in Morynzi, the birthplace of Taras Shevchenko.

Oksana Tanasiv Gallery presents closing reception of the show Code Ukraine featuring unique watercolor series by Ukrainian artist Oksana Rudenko and Oksana Tanasiv on July 29, 6-9pm
For those who wasn’t able to attend Opening Reception, join us for this unique opportunity to see new series of art by both artists. A public Closing reception will be held on Saturday, July 29, from 6pm to 9pm .

Interested collectors may call the Oksana Tanasiv Gallery to arrange a private appointment Monday-Wednesday or visit the show Thursday-Saturday , 2-6pm.
Oksana Tanasiv Gallery is located at 70 South Main Street, in the heart of SoNo, CT. The gallery is easily accessible by Metro-North and is only a 10-minute walk from the South Norwalk train station. For those traveling by car, metered street parking is available paid by credit-card or coins. Parking may also be purchased at the Haviland St and SoNo Square lot, located approximately a 5-minute walk from the gallery.

Oksana Rudenko is Ukrainian artist-refugee who escaped bombed Ukraine at the beginning of the war, when the full invasion of the country by Russia happened.
Today Oksana lives in works in Germany.

On my life's journey, I often meet people who envy other people's success. 

Jealous, they make nasty, primitive attempts to humiliate someone's success story and devalue their achievements. People who can only see the tip of the iceberg, without thinking about the depth of trials, hard work, intense self-organization, discipline behind the “beautiful facade” of success. 

They don't even realize the high price paid for this "success". Paid by years of hard work, days, sleepless nights, weeks, months, and years of intense overwhelming schedules, seven days a week, no vacations, no holidays. For decades. And without any outside help. Without compromising themselves.

I feel sorry for those primitives , because the energy they spend on envy and hatred, these intellectually and morally poor people could have spent on their own self-realization and improvement... or they will live the rest of their lives as a primitive biological mass without benefit to themselves and society.

Oksi Oksana Tanasiv
August 13, 2023

Isadora Duncan used to start her mornings like this: on a luxurious sofa, drinking coffee from a nice cup and reading the newspaper. 
The newspaper said how beautifully she danced on stage! She is built like a goddess! Her brilliant dance brings the audience into ecstasy. The smile was still on Isadora's face when she picked up the next newspaper and read it. It said that the dancer was badly built, ugly as a witch, couldn't dance, a scum, and yet here she was, climbing on stage... 
A few years later, Isadora Duncan started her mornings like this: she poured the remaining wine from the bottles in the bidet. She would dilute the glasses with cologne for strength and drink it. And then she would read the newspapers. 
And then she wisely wrote in her Autobiography: other people's opinions about us have absolutely nothing to do with us. Sometimes we don't know who we are and what we are like. Only time and life will put everything in its place, that's all. 
Only losers build their lives based on the opinions of other people. Usually, they are also losers. That's why losers tend to constantly express their opinions about successful people - they think that a successful person is exactly like them. And they are afraid of a bad opinion of themselves. It would be a terrible blow to them! 
But this is not true. Sooner or later, a successful person realizes that other people's opinions are not important. What matters is talent and tireless work. And faith in your star. "Dance, Isadora!", - shouted Esenin. And he was absolutely right. 
It's a pity that the great dancer realized too late that she shouldn't read newspapers in the morning. Or the nasty stuff online. And nothing about yourself to read or listen to at all

«Light at the End of the Tunnel» series I started in 2020 during the Covid, pandemic hitting the wold. At that time I wanted to use my art to create something bright during those «dark times» , giving the hope, and sending the message to people:

 «No matter what difficult times we live, there is always joy after sadness, smile after tears, and light after darkness. There is always the Light at the End of the Tunnel...»

Light Installations CODE are innovative acrylic light boxes with double look – day abstract look and night look with the lights coming within. Interview for Media Holding Millennium, Ukraine. 
The interview is rated in the category “Україна понад усе»

Millenium: Oksana, You are a postmodern author of more than 500 works in the styles of neo-folk, realism, surrealism, and Vanitas XXI. Tell us about your career as an artist. How did you manage to reach this level?

I didn’t expect that my art would become my life’s work and bring me to the level where I am now. At first, I did it for my own pleasure, as art therapy and a hobby, but over time I realized that I could do it professionally. Behind my success are decades of practice, improving my skills, searching for galleries, art dealers, and hundreds of exhibitions, presentations, and international shows.
